However, as we move into the early twentieth century, a few trailblazers dare to break free from these conventions by incorporating multiple shots.

One of the most striking commonalities among these trick films is the use of an interior set within a frontal proscenium frame. The camera remains stationary, never deviating from its position to follow characters or objects. This composition draws its roots from the theater and, in the case of trick films, vaudeville and magic shows. The limitations of this approach are evident in the way characters usually move side-to-side, never walking towards or away from the camera. Take, for instance, the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900). The actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis, never straying from this pattern.

The use of a frontal proscenium also means that shots tend to be long and, occasionally, medium shots. Close-ups are a rarity in these trick films from the Edison catalog, a nod to the theater and vaudeville tradition where the audience sees the entire performance at any given time, framed by the borders of the stage. As in many early films, actors rarely move towards the camera, making close-ups a distant memory.

Most early trick films adhere to the rule that one conceptual shot equals one film. This limits their length to around a minute or less, depending on the frame rate used. As a result, these films typically focus on short, vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearing acts, and quick switches, with little narrative or dramatic depth. However, upon closer inspection, you'll notice that what appears to be one conceptual shot can actually be several joined together to create a seamless illusion. Take, for example, The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), an early trick film that reveals a clever editing trick when you look closely.

The name John Taylor of Caroline was synonymous with unwavering dedication to the principles of Republicanism. As an agriculturalist by trade and a brief stint in politics, he left an indelible mark on the discourse around personal freedom and government. His passion for an agrarian lifestyle served as the foundation for his opinions on sovereignty, Constitutionality, and the judicial system. His stance was firmly rooted in his desire to preserve and promote what he deemed the most noble of all professions.

Taylor believed the United States had a unique opportunity to craft an ideal system, unencumbered by traditional constraints that often hindered the development of new societies. This blank slate allowed for the establishment of a system of self-government that he passionately advocated for. He firmly believed in the inherent rights of individuals, which he saw as interconnected – when one right was compromised, the value of the others diminished. As such, these rights should be shielded from government interference. In his view, the concept of the 'state of nature' implied that those with physical strength and cunning would thrive, but in a civilized society, this shouldn't be the case.

To create an ideal society, Taylor believed a government must be designed to account for the duality of human nature – both good and evil. He rigidly adhered to a dualistic morality, arguing that as government is exercised by humans, it will inevitably reflect both virtues and vices. He defined good principles as those that protect private property, promote agriculture, and discourage the excesses of capitalism. Taylor firmly believed that a government founded on these principles would function equitably, regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be driven by avarice and self-interest. However, he noted that self-interest, though a fundamental aspect of human nature, only became problematic when it led to the creation of sub-societies that exploited others.

Taylor, like many of his fellow Republicans, advocated for a strict construction of the Constitution. He envisioned a limited Federal government with only the powers explicitly stated in the Constitution, recognizing that an extensive Federal government would be expensive and prone to despotism. However, he also believed that a literal interpretation of the Constitution without considering the intent of its writers could lead to corruption. Furthermore, he considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, as it more explicitly described the country as a collection of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

Looking back at the data, it's clear that there was a drastic drop in commuter log submissions in the third month of our project. That was a bit disheartening, and pinpointing the cause is a challenge. It's not hard to imagine that the onset of a New England winter would lead to fewer cyclists and pedestrians commuting to campus, which could account for part of the decline. With the end of the fall semester in December comes a busy time for students and faculty, finishing up schoolwork, processing grades, and gearing up for the holiday season. It's likely that filling out the commuter log got buried under the hectic pace of the time. And then there's the month-long break that accompanies the holiday season, during which many students and faculty hardly set foot on campus. Classes resume in late January, which might explain the low number of logs for that month, too. But the low numbers in February remain a puzzle.

One possible explanation is that any project of this type tends to experience a natural ebb in enthusiasm and energy at the outset, followed by a gradual decline. To combat this trend, we launched the Carpool Challenge Week, a special campaign in March to reignite the initiative, which indeed led to an uptick in log submissions that month. This highlights one of the challenges we faced: maintaining project momentum in the face of natural fluctuations and the specific hurdles of the academic calendar.

Another hurdle we encountered is the deeply ingrained cultural preference for driving one's own car, which provides a sense of freedom, independence, and flexibility. To encourage alternative modes of commuting, we offered incentives in the form of gift certificates to local businesses like restaurants, coffee shops, and the local independent bookstore. It would have been interesting to see how larger prizes might have affected participation – think a brand-new bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car. This could have helped combat that decline in engagement we experienced. The prizes remained the same throughout the project, but if we had announced bigger and better prizes as the project progressed – say, adding a couple of bicycles in December and a hybrid or electric car in January – it's likely that participation and engagement would have increased instead of decreased.

The exchange-traded fund (ETF) is a game-changer in the world of investments. Imagine having the diversification of a mutual fund and the agility of individual stock trading all wrapped up in one convenient package. That's essentially what an ETF offers. You get the best of both worlds - the stability of a broad-based index fund and the flexibility to buy and sell as you please, even shorting or trading on margin. And the icing on the cake? ETFs come with significantly lower expense ratios compared to the average mutual fund.

Of course, there are some downsides to consider. Trading ETFs involves paying a commission, just like you would with individual stocks. But the benefits far outweigh the costs. With a staggering array of funds to choose from, you can pick and choose the ones that fit your investment goals and risk tolerance. So, what's the best way to evaluate an ETF? A savvy investor would do well to dig deeper and assess whether the touted benefits, like diversification, really deliver. For the sake of this exercise, we'll be taking a closer look at the ETF IHF and its top 10 holdings to see whether owning a single ETF can match the benefits of a diversified portfolio of individual stocks.

To keep things manageable, we're focusing on the top 10 holdings, which account for a whopping 63.58% of the ETF's assets. Here they are, along with their respective percentages. We'll use these holdings to estimate how well they represent the ETF as a whole. By normalizing their assets to 100%, we can calculate their individual contributions to a portfolio's Beta and Return, as if the portfolio consisted solely of these 10 stocks in the same proportions as the ETF.

The chart reveals an interesting finding: a portfolio consisting only of the top 10 holdings would yield a 6.11% higher return than the ETF, a 16% boost in returns. Furthermore, the Beta of this portfolio is 0.12 lower than the ETF's. This suggests that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings might offer higher returns with lower risk. But are these findings statistically significant? To find out, we'll examine the standard deviation of each of these top 10 stocks, normalized to 100%, and compare them to the ETF's accumulated standard deviation.

In the realm of poetry, Edgar Allan Poe's "Dream-Land" stands out as one of his masterpieces. The term "Thulé" pops up twice in this poem, lines 6 and 56, a nod to the ancient world that Poe was deeply familiar with. In fact, "Thulé" has its roots in Virgil's time, referring to an island north of Britain that the Greeks believed marked the edge of the known world. While Virgil did indeed use the term, there's another source that deserves credit - Poe's fascination with German literature, particularly the works of Johann Wolfgang von Goethe.

This tidbit is significant because it reveals Poe's admiration for Goethe's writing. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," points out the striking similarities between their poems, suggesting that Poe was, in fact, inspired by Goethe. The Oxford Companion to English Literature notes that Goethe was a celebrated poet, best known for his poetic drama "Faust," which was published in two parts - the first in 1808 and the second in 1832, the year of Goethe's passing. Within "Faust's" second part lies a haunting poem called "The King of Thulé," which tells the story of a king whose wife dies, leaving him heartbroken and lost in grief. He spends his days drinking and crying, eventually giving up his kingdom and life, casting his belongings into the ocean. The king's tale bears an uncanny resemblance to the protagonist in "Dream-Land," who finds himself lost in a dark, lonely world, haunted by memories of loved ones and a world devoid of color.

Poe references Thule twice in his writings, using the phrase "ultima Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and "Dream-Land" as bookends. These two poems can be seen as companion pieces, with "The King of Thulé" serving as a precursor to "Dream-Land." In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes a desolate landscape, where shadows loom large and color is absent, a world that eerily mirrors Goethe's "The King of Thulé," where the king's loss of his wife has left him a hollow shell of his former self. Given Poe's admiration for Alfred Tennyson, it's likely that he was familiar with Goethe's work through various reproductions and adaptations that were circulating after the original publication.

In the Golden State of California, if a shopper gets hurt after slipping on an applesauce spill at the grocery store and then sues the store for punitive damages, can they succeed if they prove the store manager acted with malice? The manager, Paul Martin, was told about the spill twice - once by Rich Wayne at 5:00 pm and again by Mary J. Haddigan at 5:15 pm - but chose to keep eating dinner instead of having it cleaned up by 5:30 pm. So, did Martin show a "willful and conscious disregard" for the potential harm caused by the spill? To get punitive damages, the shopper, Jennifer Palmer, will need to show that Martin knew the spill could cause harm because multiple customers had fallen in the same spot before her accident. Palmer may argue that Martin was deliberately ignoring the safety of his customers by not cleaning up the spill, especially considering six slip-and-fall incidents happened at D&D Markets in 2009. While this argument might not be a slam dunk, it's still a reasonable claim given the evidence. 

Let's take a closer look at what happened. On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, Rich Wayne told Martin about the applesauce spill, and Martin basically said he was too busy eating dinner to care. Fifteen minutes later, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also informed Martin about the spill, and he responded with the same attitude. It's no coincidence that Palmer slipped and fell on the spill at 5:30 pm, and it's no surprise that she's now suing D&D Markets for compensation and punitive damages. The question is whether Palmer has a strong enough case to win punitive damages. In California, a person can receive punitive damages if the other party acted with "oppression, fraud or malice." The law defines malice as either intending to cause harm or being downright despicable and recklessly disregarding the rights or safety of others. 

So, will the court dismiss Palmer's case or let it move forward? To determine this, we need to look at whether Martin's actions were malicious. According to the law, conduct is malicious if it's a conscious disregard of the plaintiff's rights when the defendant knows the probable harm of their actions and chooses to ignore it. In this case, Martin was aware of the potential danger of the spill because several customers had already fallen in the same area, and he still chose to do nothing. This is why Palmer's lawyer will likely argue that Martin's actions were despicable and warrant punitive damages.

Almost four years ago, I took a course in Islam at CBC, where one of the most heated debates in class centered around whether Islam is a hostile religion. This question seems even more pertinent today than ever before. Looking back on the years since 9/11, I've noticed that mass media has swung from a hostile view of Islam to an extreme level of tolerance in America. We've come a long way, and it's hard to imagine that in 2001, we wouldn't have seen a presidential candidate like Barack Obama, who has an openly acknowledged Muslim background in his family.

The Biography of the Prophet has been a fascinating study for me, as it reveals a Muhammad that contradicts what I previously thought. What I knew of Muhammad's history suggested he was a forceful leader who forced conversions to Islam, conquering tribes and imposing his faith on them. However, the biography portrays Muhammad as a humble, misunderstood, and even self-effacing martyr, who attracted followers one by one through the truth of his teachings.

Some striking similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the miracles attributed to Muhammad have also caught my attention. One such example is when Muhammad multiplied mutton and milk to feed forty men, much like the miracle stories associated with Jesus. I suspect that the writers aimed to present Muhammad as a humble prophet who didn't need to prove himself, but lived in truth and performed miracles. This approach, in my view, diminishes the significance of Jesus' life and miracles, much like taking credit for someone else's achievements.

Furthermore, the biography seems to be driven by an agenda to provide evidence of witness and spontaneous conversions to Islam, with many stories presented through third-party accounts. This makes me skeptical, as it diminishes the authenticity of the stories and implies a level of fabrication. It's as if they're trying to create a narrative that undermines the integrity of the original accounts.

What bothers me most about this work is the attempt to portray Muhammad as a godly figure, humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. History, however, suggests that Muhammad's rise to power was far from gentle, and I wonder if today's Muslims are aware of the true complexities behind their prophet's story.

The teachings of Jesus and the core beliefs he held during his life were quickly lost in the sands of time as Christianity evolved after his passing. When we view this history from a broad perspective, we notice a trend of Christianity drifting further and further away from its roots. Today, we're witnessing a growing awareness and an unprecedented shift towards progress. While traditionalists cling to the status quo and resist any departure from established dogma, this segment of the population may not hold enough sway to shape the entire narrative. As time progresses, a growing awareness of Christian history will emerge, and a yearning will develop to distinguish the doctrines that have been added to Christianity over the centuries from the original intent of the faith's namesake. It may take decades or even centuries, but the inevitable outcome will be a reversal of the trend in Christian history. The movement will slowly but surely peel back the layers of doctrine, reversing the clock as it were, until only the fundamental principles introduced by Jesus on behalf of God remain. When this shift sweeps through the United States and Europe, influencing the masses, the church as an institution will continue to thrive, but its teachings will become more uniform and less diverse. Regions, denominations, and divisions will begin to resemble each other more closely, rather than showcasing their differences. History is replete with examples of such reversions – consider how the Roman Empire once persecuted Christians, only to later become a bastion of Christianity, or how the United States transitioned from slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversion that's on the horizon will play out in the realm of the Christian faith, as we seek to return to the source and, in the process, shed our diversity. A crucial aspect of this journey will be reinterpreting Jesus' words as metaphors rather than literal statements. So, what's changed since Jesus' time?

Looking back through the mists of history, we find that the only existing faith was Judaism, the theological foundation of the Christian religion. By the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., monotheism, divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were established at the core of this faith. However, the Jewish population was not a monolith; they divided into the Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the common people, each with their own distinct perspectives.

The Jungle is a thought-provoking novel that forces us to confront the harsh realities of human nature. Beneath the surface, we're all driven by our own self-interest, prioritizing our own desires above the needs of others. This self-centeredness is starkly evident in the novel's portrayal of the factory owners and managers, who are consumed by their quest for wealth and power. Their relentless pursuit of growth and expansion knows no bounds, leaving a trail of destruction in its wake. The factory's imposing silhouette against the sky, with its towering chimneys spewing forth smoke and pollution, serves as a powerful metaphor for the devastating impact of their actions.

According to Upton Sinclair's masterful depiction, the owners' disregard for the well-being of their employees is matched only by their disdain for the environment. The pollution and filth that pervade Packingtown are a testament to their callous disregard for the consequences of their actions. The workers, meanwhile, are nothing more than pawns in the owners' game of profit and greed, forced to toil in dehumanizing conditions with little regard for their safety or dignity.

The owners' treatment of their employees is a stark reminder of the exploitation that exists in the world. They'll stop at nothing to maximize profits, even if it means sacrificing the livelihoods of their workers. The speed and intensity of the production line, combined with the ever-present threat of layoffs and unemployment, creates a culture of fear and desperation. With little to no protection from the law, workers are forced to endure the harshest conditions, their lives reduced to a mere commodity to be exploited.

While the novel doesn't explicitly state it, the workers in Packingtown are little more than modern-day slaves, their lives controlled by the whims of their oppressors. The lack of support systems, combined with the corrupting influence of unions that prey on the vulnerable, only serves to perpetuate the cycle of exploitation. The consequences of this system are dire, with immorality and despair becoming nearly inevitable outcomes for those trapped within its grasp.

When authors aim to evoke a particular feeling or attitude in their readers, they often employ various techniques to achieve this goal. Some methods prove more effective than others, and F. Scott Fitzgerald skillfully employs a range of these techniques in his novel, The Great Gatsby. To create a specific ambiance around a subject, Fitzgerald pairs seemingly incongruous adjectives and nouns, while also attributing meaning to symbols and using them for the same purpose. He takes this latter approach with numerous colors, including gold, green, white, and red, weaving intricate meanings for these hues throughout the novel. 

In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald masterfully builds up the significance of colors, particularly white and red, then harnesses this meaning to elicit a particular emotional response in readers when applied to significant objects. When it comes to white/gray, Fitzgerald creates a sense of uniformity, with white representing a touch of elegance and refinement, while gray signifies age and faded grandeur. He sets the stage for this interpretation from the novel's outset, frequently using both colors in various contexts. For example, Daisy and Jordan are frequently "in white," and everyone, including Nick, wears white attire at Gatsby's party - Tom dons a "white shirt," and Catherine is described as "powdered milky white." Notably, the only time people are not dressed in white is when Nick is describing the impressions he formed of Gatsby's party, where the atmosphere is dominated by "primary colors." Fitzgerald further solidifies the meaning of these colors by applying them to mundane, inconsequential subjects: as Nick navigates his daily routine, he walks through "the white chasms of lower New York," and the names on his schedule become "gray names." He also describes ordinary people or places as white or gray: Jordan and Daisy share a "white girlhood," the valley of ashes is characterized by "gray cars and gray land," and the dog-seller is a "gray old man." 

After establishing the meaning of white/gray, Fitzgerald uses these colors to convey a sense of unimportance or uniformity to certain subjects, beginning with Daisy. After an extended period of relative absence, Fitzgerald reintroduces white as a descriptor for Daisy, depicting her dressed in "a little white roadster," thereby reducing her in the reader's eyes from a fully fleshed-out character to a mere uniform ideal, something Gatsby covets and yearns for. This technique is also employed around Daisy, reinforcing the notion that she is a uniform addition, as seen in the "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" and her appearance in a "white" dress prior to Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

The sun-kissed county of San Diego is a haven for agricultural productivity, with its idyllic climate yielding a bountiful harvest of delicious crops. Tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, and an array of herbs, tree fruits, and berries thrive in this Mediterranean haven. The demand for organic community-supported agriculture is also on the rise in the area, with numerous organizations experiencing lengthy waiting lists for their fresh produce. Locals can also indulge in organic eggs, milk, and honey, and many farms offer tours, allowing visitors to connect with nature and appreciate the beauty of the land.

However, the benefits of organic farming come at a cost. The absence of chemicals in the soil and water leads to greater biodiversity in the area, but it also demands more labor and management to control pests and weeds, as well as to maintain soil fertility. Compared to conventional farming methods, organic farming often incurs higher losses and lacks the efficiency of larger operations. Moreover, small-scale organic farming requires more manual effort to implement beneficial practices like cover cropping, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and managing plant growth to create specific conditions for wildlife. As a result, landowners in this scenario may seek financial assistance or expert guidance to maximize their profits while preserving the land's ecological integrity.

The chosen property is a 160-acre tract of land adjacent to the charming town of Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County, California. This diverse landscape comprises chaparral, non-native grasslands, and oak woodlands, situated next to the Cleveland National Forest. The property falls within the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan, which currently considers over a hundred species of flora and fauna, many of which are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat and the mountain yellow-legged frog.

This land has a rich history, having been inhabited by Native Americans for centuries and later settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 19th century. The property was originally part of a homestead patent, likely used for grazing and wood production over the years. To explore the possibilities for a small farmer in this area, I researched government programs and chose a model from a nearby organic farm in the same region.

The intricate dance of culture plays a profound role in the delicate art of negotiation. But what exactly is culture? It's not a straightforward concept, as it's defined by both what it is and what it signifies. Culture is multifaceted, diverse, and far from uniform. Making broad statements like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" does more harm than good, oversimplifying the complexities of a culture. A more constructive approach is to grasp the significance of a culture to the negotiation at hand and how its values will influence the conversation. When interacting with a foreign culture, we inevitably compare it to our own, and a deeper understanding can be gained by studying its history, biases, and traditions.

Rather than judging or trying to change a culture, it's essential to accept it for what it is, working within its boundaries, especially during negotiations. This is particularly crucial when you find yourself in a weaker bargaining position. Similarly, when negotiating in unfamiliar territory, respecting local customs and traditions can help break down cultural barriers and facilitate progress.

It's also essential to recognize that culture doesn't solely exist within national or international contexts. Corporate cultures within a single nation can be vastly different, shaped by factors such as work hours, communication styles, and hiring practices. Take the varying corporate cultures within the United States, for example, which can differ significantly from company to company and even within the same company from one region to another. This diversity of thought within a societal culture is a reflection of the complex, multifaceted nature of human experience.

Understanding values is equally crucial, as they reveal the underlying motivations and priorities of a culture. In cultures where saving face or communal harmony are valued, a negotiator is unlikely to publicly embarrass their company or superior to achieve success. Conversely, in cultures that prioritize a hard-driven bargain, negotiators may not be inclined to settle quickly. By considering these generalities before the negotiation, you'll be better equipped to navigate the complexities of cross-cultural communication. However, don't underestimate the importance of getting to know your opponent on a personal level – it's a key factor in effective negotiation.

The phrase "The fool hath said in his heart, 'There is no God'" first appears in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and serves as the starting point for St. Anselm's argument on the existence of God. This notion also resonates with Thomas Aquinas, another influential thinker we'll be exploring. Since both authors aim to prove the same concept, we'll begin by assuming they're correct in their belief in a God-like entity, specifically the God of the Bible. Examining alternative, non-Biblical concepts of God would skew our comparison, as their arguments are fundamentally in defense of this particular notion of divinity. So, let's dive into their arguments, keeping in mind that each makes some compelling points, yet neither provides a comprehensive foundation for believing in God.

To illustrate this, let's start by dissecting St. Anselm's argument. Anselm's reasoning is centered around gaining understanding through faith, exploring the depths of one's own mind to find proof of God. He proposes that because God exists within our understanding, we can't conceive of his nonexistence. In essence, Anselm suggests that the proof for God lies within the confines of our own minds, and that we don't need external evidence to confirm his existence. This idea relies on the concept of faith, which, within Christian texts, refers to accepting truths without empirical proof. This line of thinking often raises eyebrows, as it seems to defy the need for concrete evidence.

In stark contrast, Thomas Aquinas takes a more cerebral approach. He argues that the existence of God can be proven solely through reason and empirical evidence, eliminating the need for faith altogether. This perspective would be particularly valuable in evangelism, a vital aspect of Christianity, as it would allow for the recruitment of new followers without relying on their willingness to accept the unproven. Instead, logic would be the driving force behind their conversion. Aquinas presents five logical arguments in support of God's existence: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each showcases the logical necessity for God's existence, demonstrating that we can deduce the existence of the missing piece (God) even when it's not directly visible, much like completing a puzzle.

About 2500 years ago, in ancient times, a prince was born who would eventually be known as the Buddha. Throughout his life, he rejected worldly pursuits, achieved enlightenment, and his teachings gave rise to Buddhism. However, the faith has undergone significant changes over the centuries. This transformation is apparent in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed, a tradition that was never explicitly taught by the Buddha himself. These changes span from superficial customs to the very core of the faith, encompassing both the monastic and lay perspectives. The Theravada Buddhist community has had to adapt its core principles over time due to external and internal influences, both benevolent and malevolent.

In this discussion, certain terms will be used extensively. 'Internal force' refers to any change originating within the Buddhist community, while 'external force' denotes any influence from non-Buddhists. A 'hostile force' is any influence that seeks to harm or damage the Buddhist community, often stemming from a negative perception of Buddhism. Conversely, a 'benign force' does not intend to harm or help the community, though its outcomes may be unintentionally detrimental or beneficial.

Let's delve into the fundamental principles of Theravada Buddhism, which form the bedrock of the faith. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is comprised of the Tripitaka, consisting of the Sutta Pitaka, Vinaya Pitaka, and Abhidhamma Pitaka. The Sutta Pitaka houses the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka outlines the monastic disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka deals with the metaphysical aspects of Buddhism. These concepts include Anatta (no fixed self), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Recognizing these ideas is crucial to breaking free from Sansara, the cycle of birth and death, and eventually, attaining enlightenment, thereby ending lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). The Vinaya Pitaka outlines rules for laymen, including the five precepts (non-harming, truthfulness, non-stealing, chastity, and abstinence from intoxicants), while monks adhere to numerous additional rules. The four noble truths, a fundamental Buddhist concept, state that life is marked by Dukkha, attachment causes suffering, and that suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico - a tale of a 57-year rivalry that spanned the years from 1836 to 1893. It's a story of clashes, compromises, and a long, winding road to eventual understanding. The rivalry, which reached its peak in the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, was a defining moment in the history of both nations. The war saw the United States emerge victorious, claiming Texas and the American Southwest as its own. However, it wasn't the only confrontation between the two countries. There were many skirmishes, disputes, and standoffs that continued to simmer until just before the outbreak of World War I.

At the heart of the rivalry were fundamental disagreements over issues like faith, culture, and tradition. The two nations also had competing material interests, which often led to confrontations. This pattern is all too familiar in the world of international relations, where nations sharing a border often find themselves at odds over competing interests. The United States and Mexico are just one example of many long-standing rivalries that have shaped the complex web of relationships between nations.

Historians like David M. Pletcher have noted that the United States has had its fair share of diplomatic headaches over the years, particularly with Mexico and Cuba. These two countries, due to their proximity to the United States, have often found themselves at odds with American interests. In contrast, many other Latin American nations have enjoyed relatively smooth relations with the United States.

Religious differences were another point of contention between the United States and Mexico. This was a trend that echoed throughout history, as nations have often been driven apart by fundamental disagreements over faith and governance. Sally Frahm observed that Americans have historically been wary of Catholicism and monarchy, just as they were opposed to fascism and communism in the 20th century. This ideological divide was deeply rooted in the distrust that existed between the English and Spanish empires, which in turn had a lasting impact on the relationship between the United States and Mexico.

Diehl and Goerts documented 17 significant disputes between Mexico and the United States during this 57-year period, with most of them centering on territorial issues, border raids, and frontier problems. The issue of bandits and outlaws crossing the border was a recurring problem that only began to subside when both countries fortified their borders. As Schmitt pointed out, the rivalry between the two nations began to dissipate as Mexico became increasingly dependent on the United States, and American interests shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico.

It's hard to believe it's been fifteen years since my life was turned upside down by a mysterious illness that I'd never even heard of. At the time, I was living my dream as a nurse, a career I'd chosen to escape the uncertainty of my own childhood. The mantra I'd heard over and over as I grew up was, "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick." So, I put my aspirations of becoming a scientist or journalist on the backburner and pursued nursing instead.

Fast forward to my 46th birthday, and I was faced with a harsh reality: I was struggling to make ends meet, with no savings to speak of, and unable to work due to my illness. Fifteen years later, I'm still living on Social Security Disability, and I've lost everything that was once mine. Every day is a grueling battle to maintain my security, safety, and self-respect. Yet, amidst the chaos, I've come to realize one invaluable truth: when disaster strikes, we all need a little help from our friends and family, no matter how strong we think we are. And trust me, when real disaster hits, strength is the last thing you feel like you possess.

My point is that life is unpredictable, and emergencies can lurk around every corner, big or small. No matter how well-prepared we think we are, some challenges are simply too big to tackle alone.

I agree that we should be cautious about relying too heavily on government support, but I firmly believe that Americans would be better off learning to trust and help one another rather than turning to individualism as a solution. The idea of rugged individualism that our country was built on is a myth; it was actually the compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources of our forefathers that carried them through tough times. The pioneers who crossed the country in wagon trains didn't make it on their own; they had each other.

So, by all means, be prepared – I've got my disaster kit and emergency supplies ready. I've got flashlights, first aid supplies, and a stash of canned goods, just in case. But while it's essential to be prepared, it's equally important to build a community that looks out for one another. Get to know your neighbors, and who knows, you might just find a lifeline when you need it most.

Evolution's intricate dance - what drives it forward? Are there unseen forces that shape the course of change in the natural world? It's a question that has puzzled scientists for centuries, from D'Arcy Thompson's groundbreaking statements in 1917 to the present day. Despite the advances in mathematical modeling, the complexity of organic forms remains a mystery waiting to be unraveled. Recent studies, however, have applied mathematical modeling to the intricate processes of mollusk skeletogenesis, both during development and evolution (Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our research delves into how mathematically modeling ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, combined with experimental studies, can shed light on the mechanisms behind evolutionary-developmental change.

We used high-tech X-ray images of Prunum species to quantify key parameters that can be used to model hypothetical and actual shell morphologies. These parameters were then fed into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995) to create a virtual framework for understanding the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. By combining these results with experimental and observational studies, we aim to gain a deeper understanding of the underlying forces that shape macroevolutionary events in this group.

A shell can be visualized as a dynamic, three-dimensional structure that grows and changes over time, like a spiral that unwinds through 360 degrees of space. Each coil is called a whorl, which spirals around an imaginary central axis, or columella, that runs through the shell's central column. The rate at which whorls expand can vary, and the continuous lines separating each whorl are called sutures. In most shells, the last whorl, or body whorl, is the largest. The spire is the collective whorls excluding the last one, while the apex is the spire's tip and the base is the opposite end. The animal emerges from its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed from different angles - apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural - with the "classic" view being the apertural perspective, where the aperture faces the viewer and the apex points upwards.

To count whorls, start by viewing the shell from the apical angle and mark where the first suture begins. Draw a line dividing the shell in two, then count the whorls from this line, estimating to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures that traverse time and space as the animal builds its shell. By tracking the center of each whorl's aperture and its horizontal and vertical radius, we can map the shell's path through space and time. This trajectory can be represented graphically and mathematically, allowing us to manipulate the parameters and explore the mollusk's skeletogenesis in greater detail.

We've all been watching Indonesia struggle to make headway in reducing neonatal and infant mortality rates over the past decade. Despite making strides in meeting some of the Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation targets, the country has been woefully slow to improve child and maternal health. This plateau highlights the need to strengthen the overall health system rather than pinning our hopes on targeted programmatic interventions.

The statistics are telling. While 72% of births in Indonesia now involve a skilled health worker, this figure is somewhat misleading because it includes traditional workers like midwives who aren't equipped to handle complications. The consequence is a high number of maternal deaths caused by hemorrhage. Moreover, the rate of diarrheal cases in children under five treated by a health professional has been on the decline. Unfortunately, data on postnatal care is incomplete, and what we do have suggests that this area is a major concern, with low rates across the country.

Cesarian-section rates are still disconcertingly low at 4% nationwide, but the disparity between urban and rural areas is even more striking. While 7% of urban births involve a C-section, this rate drops to an alarming 2% in rural areas. This stark contrast highlights the issue of unequal access to healthcare services, with urban areas reaping the lion's share of the benefits. Another pressing concern is vertical equity: there's a staggering 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles. This means the poor are struggling to access healthcare services, largely due to the financial burden of out-of-pocket costs.

So, what's the way forward? The fundamental question is how to effectively address the glaring lack of services. Should Indonesia focus on targeted programmatic approaches or strengthen the overall health system? While program-specific solutions may seem attractive, yielding faster results and more manageable objectives, they have their drawbacks. Investing heavily in one area can divert resources from other essential areas, drawing human resources towards the most funded sectors. Moreover, running multiple parallel programs can lead to duplication of services, uncoordinated between programs, resulting in increased paperwork and administrative burdens.

Victorian novels are known for their meticulous attention to detail and their focus on the lives of the aristocracy of the time period. However, two works that deviate from this norm are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. Both novels incorporate elements of mystery and a touch of the bizarre, characteristics that were not typical of novels from the era. These unconventional features serve to strengthen the characters within each novel, offering valuable insights into their motivations and emotions.

As the characters navigated the chaotic world around them, their minds were flooded with a multitude of bewildering ideas. The lines between reality and fantasy began to blur, and it seemed as though they were trapped in a never-ending cycle of confusion. In Oliver Twist, for instance, the protagonist's inner turmoil is revealed through his dreamlike states and hallucinations. These strange visions offer a glimpse into Oliver's inner world, exposing his deepest fears and pains. The vivid description of the shooting in chapter 28 is a prime example of this. Oliver's reliving of the traumatic event is a stark reminder of the lack of control he had over his circumstances, and the devastating impact it had on his health.

The passage is a poignant portrayal of Oliver's emotional state, as he struggles to come to terms with the dire reality of his situation. His hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit serve as a constant reminder of the pain and fear that he endured. The "unseen hand" that swept him away is a powerful symbol of the overwhelming forces that controlled his life, leaving him feeling powerless and defeated. The passage implies that Oliver's experiences have broken him, rendering him incapable of taking control of his own life, even in the face of danger.

In a similar vein, the novel Wuthering Heights employs dreamlike sequences to reveal the inner workings of its characters' minds. The passage from Wuthering Heights describes a sense of time and space that is distorted and disjointed, reflecting the characters' emotional states. The day and night seem to blend together, creating a sense of timelessness and desperation. This portrayal of the characters' inner world serves to underscore their emotional turmoil and the sense of being trapped in a world beyond their control.

A couple of years ago, I had the chance to work with elementary school students in an after-school program, where I tried to help them with their academic struggles, particularly in English and reading. However, I was approached by one of the instructors to assist a young boy named Adrian, who was in third or fourth grade. What struck me was that his reading difficulties didn't seem to follow the usual pattern. Some letters he could pronounce flawlessly, while others left him completely stumped. It was baffling, especially since he spoke perfect English. I had a hunch that his linguistic background might be the key, and I was right. His mother, who walked in on me while babysitting, only spoke Spanish, and I realized that Adrian's issue wasn't reading per se, but rather not knowing the English alphabet. This epiphany revealed to me how easily language barriers can masquerade as reading difficulties. I'm not sure how much it helped Adrian, but I hope he's made progress since then.

I share this story to highlight the complexities of language barriers in schools, particularly in California, and to show that the issue isn't always as straightforward as we think. Even for children who speak perfect English, reading can still be a significant hurdle. It's clear that this problem exists, so what can we do about it? In Adrian's case, the solution was simple: targeted tutoring in English reading, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation. However, for children who barely speak English, the solution is far more intricate. There is no single answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, and ESL classes, each by itself, won't solve this problem. The key lies in combining these approaches.

The dual language system is an excellent concept that can benefit all children, not just those whose first language is Spanish. Research has shown that "children in two-way bilingual education programs have been found to outperform their peers academically." Many people fear that such programs will waste resources and only benefit a minority of students, but this is a misconception. If implemented as the standard, rather than an exception, all children would benefit from these programs. So, how can we make this happen? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? That would be unrealistic and impractical. Instead, we can have bilingual aids, tutors, or support staff to help.

We're often fed the notion that there's something greater than us, something we can't fully grasp since childhood. Some of us head to Sunday school, others to the temple, while many more turn inward in search of answers. Many of us simply accept the faiths passed down by our parents, but some of us reject them outright, convinced that there's nothing beyond our own understanding. We may adopt one value system only to later replace it with another. Ultimately, our journey is about defining ourselves through our unique perspectives on spirituality, seeking a guiding light in the darkness to lead us from the shadows into the light.

[PAUSE]

I remember a conversation with my dad, sitting on our porch as the rain poured down around us. We sat amidst the sound of raindrops pounding on the tin roof, surrounded by the dying plants along the edge of the porch. My dad's eyes were lost in thought, gazing out into the rain with a mix of introspection and reminiscence. He'd grown thinner and frailer over the past few months, his hair thinned out, and his clothes hung loosely on his frame. I sensed a deep sadness, a sense of unease, and a reluctance to confront the reality of his impending loss. I hugged him, sat back down, and joined him in staring out into the rain-soaked evening.

My dad passed away just five days after my twenty-second birthday in December. The chemo and radiation had prolonged his life by a few months, but it only prolonged his suffering. I couldn't help but wonder, what kind of higher power would do this? As I lay alone in the dark that night, I didn't say any prayers. If there was a God, I thought, he had stopped listening to me long ago.

I chose not to watch my dad's final days. I couldn't bear to witness the life that created me slipping away. I wanted to remember my dad as he lived, not as he died. I knew him better than anyone else did, and I was certain he wouldn't have wanted me to be there for his passing. I curled up in a ball in bed for three days, waiting for the news.

But the phone never rang.

The term "Gothic Novel" is a paradox in and of itself, as literary critic Ian Watt so aptly described it as an "oxymoron for 'Old-New.'" [The Rise of the Gothic Novel] The Gothic mode has been subject to a range of reactions, from scathing criticism to fervent praise, with some accusing it of lacking depth and others lauding its ability to evoke a sense of the "terrible sublime" (Burke).  Interestingly, the genre's birthplace can be attributed to Horace Walpole's 18th-century masterpiece, The Castle of Otranto, which successfully blended elements of both "ancient" and "modern" romances to create a new literary form.  Walpole cleverly combined "old" theatrical elements with the "new" narrative style of modern novels to craft a story he dubbed "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre draws heavily from medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions, often incorporating them in a way that adds to its mystique. At the time of The Castle of Otranto's publication, the term "gothic" was already being used to describe various cultures, styles, and eras, often with a hint of nostalgia or even disdain for what was perceived as outdated or unsophisticated in the face of modern advancements. The union of the theatrical "Gothic" with the novel's innovative format, which allowed readers a more intimate glimpse into the characters' psychology, enabled the Gothic genre to endure for centuries, becoming both nostalgic and new to readers from different eras.

One of the most enduring Gothic ideas is the concept of Chivalry, which has its roots in medieval times. The original Gothic novel, The Castle of Otranto, explores this idea, adapting and transmuting it to create a sense of an idealized past. Chivalry, with its associations of bravery, honor, and competence, was crucial to Gothic writers like Walpole, who saw it as a lost ideal in their own time. Through the use of chivalric concepts and mannerisms, the "gothic past" becomes romanticized and idealized, hinting at the future evolution of Gothic into Romantic literature. As Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto during a tumultuous period in history, he may have believed that the supposed morality and goodness of the Gothic era had been lost in modern society. This sentiment is evident in the character of Frederic, who embodies many chivalric traits, including being a prince, having suffered tragedy, and being described in a way that exaggerates traditional chivalric images. This character serves as a precursor to the Gothic trope of excess, which would become a hallmark of the genre (66).

The concept of supply chain management has been evolving rapidly over the years, and I've seen firsthand the transformation of the way companies manage their goods movement from raw materials to the final customer. The term 'supply chain management' was coined in 1982 by Keith Oliver, a consultant who recognized the importance of streamlining the process to meet customer demands efficiently. The entire supply chain process involves planning, implementing, and controlling various stages to ensure customer satisfaction. At its core, supply chain management is about orchestrating the six key elements: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information to provide exceptional customer service.

Production is where it all begins. It's the foundation upon which the entire supply chain is built. This stage involves outlining the when, why, where, and how of production, which requires managers to stay attuned to customer needs. By analyzing market trends, managers can gauge what customers are demanding and decide what products to produce, in what quantities, and where to produce them to meet customer expectations. The location for production is critical, as it affects volume and quality, so managers must weigh these factors carefully.

Once production is underway, managers focus on scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. Every detail is crucial, as any misstep can lead to costly delays and inefficiencies down the line. I've seen this firsthand in my retail days at places like Wal-Mart and Target, where even the smallest processes – from employee uniforms to receiving shipments – are meticulously planned and executed to ensure a seamless customer experience.

The next key element is supply, which involves strategic decisions about core capabilities and outsourcing partnerships. Companies often have multiple divisions for a single product, each with its own equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers must decide which division is best suited for each process and may choose to outsource work to other companies to boost velocity – the ability to deliver high-quality products while keeping costs low. By outsourcing, companies can tap into new capabilities and expertise, allowing them to stay competitive in the market.

I was staring at a haunting message scrawled on a cardboard sign held aloft by Ellen Page, the talented actress from Juno. "Hitler is alive in Burma," it read, the words etched with a Sharpie in bold, stark letters. I couldn't help but wonder about the tumultuous history of Burma, now known as Myanmar, a Southeast Asian nation ruled by a ruthless military junta that seized power in 1962 through a sudden coup. In 2007, a wave of protests erupted, led by courageous Burmese monks clad in their distinctive saffron robes. Dubbed the "Saffron Revolution," these gatherings marked a rare moment of public defiance in a decade of silence. However, the government's initial hesitation to crack down was short-lived, and soon the violence escalated into a brutal conflict between the monks and the military, with troops invading and ransacking monasteries across the country. Foreign journalists were rounded up and imprisoned, with a Japanese photojournalist, Kenji Nagai, tragically killed on September 27th, 2007, simply for witnessing a street protest. Estimates of the death toll varied, with some reports claiming as few as 13 fatalities, while Colonel Hla Win, a former army officer, whispered a chilling truth: "Many more people have been killed in recent days than you've been told. There are thousands of bodies to count."

This is a story as old as civilization itself. Throughout history, governments have sought to suppress dissent and maintain complete control over their citizens. Ancient Roman emperors declared themselves divine rulers, while Japanese emperors were believed to be gods, sent to guide their people to prosperity – or so they claimed. Our own President George W. Bush allegedly held weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of the self-proclaimed Stupid People Worldwide, a group that seemed to be an offshoot of the Republican Party.

There have been countless examples of these power-hungry tactics. The 1989 Tiananmen Square protests, where students, intellectuals, and labor activists dared to challenge the Chinese government, resulted in a mysterious death toll that ranged from 200 to a staggering 3,000. The Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, backed by the Rwandan government, systematically slaughtered Tutsis and political moderates, was another egregious example. And then, of course, there's the infamous Holocaust, where Hitler's 'Third Reich' machinery rounded up and killed millions of Jews.

The impact of Duke Ellington's legacy in jazz is largely due to his remarkable longevity and, by extension, his incredible ability to push the boundaries of his orchestra through his creative vision. While his piano playing is often understated in many of his compositions, as a composer Ellington excelled in crafting rich and complex pieces that showcased the unique talents of each band member. He skillfully designed the framework for soloists to improvise freely, as well as writing tightly orchestrated sections that highlighted the distinctive style of individual musicians, all while maintaining a cohesive tone for the entire orchestra. Through this approach, Ellington managed to create some of the most groundbreaking and brilliant pieces in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary highlights Ellington's innovative use of voice as a jazz instrument, as seen in Creole Love Call, an early example of using voice to add texture and depth without the constraints of lyrics. This piece demonstrates Ellington's ability to complement the style of his soloists, a trait evident throughout his career. The 12-bar blues piece features six distinct choruses, including a call and response between voice and reeds, a muted trumpet solo, a sweeping clarinet solo, a full-band echo of the first chorus, a climactic reed-driven chorus, and a final chorus with a return to the call and response structure, where the voice takes on the sound of the "growl" technique. A brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant trombone ending rounds out the piece.

Ellington's use of voice to add a dimension of tone color is a stylistic trait that permeates his work. In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year after Creole Love Call, Ellington combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color, creating a rich and complementary sound through a call and response phrase between Bubber Miley's muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing. This technique is further explored in It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing), where Ellington uses Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone. These examples showcase Ellington's mastery of creating innovative and harmonious sounds that bring out the best in his musicians.

It's a nagging feeling that's been haunting her since she was 14. A yearning that refused to be satiated, growing stronger with each passing year. At 17, it was still there, gnawing at her insides. She'd initially thought it was a desire for something, but as the years went by, she realized it was actually a longing for someone. However, the people who had caught her attention just didn't seem to fit the bill. She found herself questioning this peculiar affliction, trying to pinpoint its source, but nothing seemed to stick. The years of contemplation had yielded a multitude of theories, yet none of them felt quite right.

Those were usually the days when life was idyllic at home. Her parents were a tranquil couple who rarely argued with each other, and when they did, it was usually over her desire for independence and free-spirited nature. She, the free-spirited daughter of calm parents, brought a whirlwind of energy to the household. It was a dynamic that worked surprisingly well, and her likability made it easy for people to warm up to her.

But today was a different story. As she wandered through the house, searching for inspiration, the serene atmosphere was shattered by a blood-curdling scream from the kitchen. Her mother's voice, a melodious sound, was now laced with distress. Panic set in as she rushed to the kitchen, her mind racing with worst-case scenarios. "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" she exclaimed, dashing into the room. Her mother was on the ground, writhing in agony, her words barely above a whisper. "Ow...sweetie, I...need you to take me to...the hospital." The desperation in her voice was palpable, and her daughter sprang into action. "Okay, Mom, where can I pick you up?" she asked, trying to keep her cool. Her mother's directions were fragmented, but her daughter was grateful for the classes that had honed her physical strength. She carefully lifted her mother and placed her in the car, driving her to the hospital with a sense of purpose.

The hospital's sterile scent and eerie atmosphere only added to the tension, but her daughter's focus was solely on her mother. She quickly ushered her into a treatment room, called out for medical help, and watched as the doctors and nurses swarmed in to attend to her mother's wounds. It turned out her mother had taken a tumble off a step stool while reaching for a vase on the top shelf of their kitchen cabinet. The worry etched on her face gave way to relief as the medical team sprang into action, and she waited anxiously for news about her mother's condition.

A recent study shed light on the benefits of following the Mediterranean Diet, also known as the Med diet. The study found that women who adhered to this diet, as reflected by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," had a lower risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke. The aMed diet is a variation of the Med diet that emphasizes plant-based foods, such as fruits, nuts, whole grains, legumes, and fish, while reducing consumption of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol intake is also allowed.

Past research has consistently shown that a Med diet is associated with a reduced risk of total and heart-related mortality. In fact, one study found that the Med diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and improving cholesterol levels in obese individuals. However, previous studies did not focus specifically on the relationship between the Med diet and stroke or stroke mortality.

This new study, which followed 74,886 female nurses over a 20-year period, discovered a significant association between higher aMed diet scores and lower risks of CHD and stroke. The study used data from the Nurses' Health Study, a large cohort study that has been monitoring the health of 121,700 female nurses since 1984. The researchers computed the aMed diet score six times between 1984 and 2004, using self-reported food frequency questionnaires that assessed nutrient intake over the previous year. The study found that a high aMed diet score was associated with a 29% lower risk of CHD and a 29% lower risk of stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile.

To minimize random variation and better capture long-term dietary habits, the researchers averaged the aMed scores from multiple questionnaires. They also adjusted for various confounding factors, such as age, smoking status, body mass index, menopausal status, and physical activity. The study's findings suggest that following a Mediterranean-style diet may be an effective way to reduce the risk of heart disease and stroke in women.

We're still reeling from the aftermath of the 2007 financial crisis that ravaged the United States. The unemployment rate skyrocketed, the housing market imploded, and some of America's most influential corporations were left in shambles. So, let's face it – we're still wondering: how did this disaster unfold, and what can we do to prevent it from happening again? In a nutshell, the crisis was born from a toxic mix of self-serving and naive decision-making that forced banks and financial institutions to hand out sub-prime loans into a fragile financial ecosystem. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were strong-armed into underwriting and repackaging these mortgages into CDOs and CDSs. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks found themselves woefully underfunded, and the chaos spilled over into the re-packaged mortgages they'd sold, ultimately infecting the entire economy.

But the seeds of this disaster were sown back in the late 1990s, when the Clinton administration was hell-bent on securing a second term in office. To bolster his popularity, they relaxed lending restrictions, creating a perfect storm for the sub-prime crisis that would unfold seven years later. In 1999, New York Times journalist Steven Holmes pointed out the impending doom: "Fannie Mae, the nation's largest mortgage underwriter, was under intense pressure from the Clinton administration to expand mortgage loans to low- and moderate-income households, all while satisfying shareholder demands for phenomenal growth in profits." Holmes astutely predicted the consequences of these actions: "But the government-subsidized corporation might struggle in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to the savings and loan industry in the 1980s." As we now know, the results were catastrophic.

A perfect storm of factors contributed to the economic meltdown, including the increasingly complex mortgage landscape. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) became ubiquitous in the years leading up to the crisis, entangling more sectors of the economy in the housing market. This created a housing bubble that left U.S. households and financial markets paper-thin, vulnerable to even the slightest price fluctuations.

In the end, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were left reeling. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported a staggering $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt in 2007, equivalent to about 30% of the USA's GDP. Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at fire-sale prices, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subject to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were brought under government control in September 2008.

The agony and ecstasy of exposition.  That pivotal moment in your story where you spread your wings and soar, leaving your readers in awe of your masterful prose - or, conversely, nodding off to sleep with a silent curse.  Dr. Merlin has been known to slam her monitor in frustration when she finds herself bogged down in Too Much Information, and not in the good kind of way.

Exposition: the nemesis that worms its way into every writer's narrative, begging to be told - and told in excruciating detail.  We've all heard the mantra, "Show, don't tell," but even seasoned writers like Dr. Merlin still find themselves succumbing to the lure of lengthy passages that leave the reader wondering what's happening.  It's the inner voice that whispers, "Get the backstory out of the way so we can get to the good stuff," but in truth, it's often the devil in disguise.

Exposition is the act of telling the reader what happened, in straightforward prose.  In film, it's the character's info dump, à la "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, it's the author's way of telling, not showing.  And let's face it, it's a slippery slope.  

Consider this example: a heroine meets her beloved, gets married in a grand ceremony, and her husband is murdered before her eyes.  You wouldn't expect this entire sequence to unfold over two pages, with only two lines of dialogue from each character.  You'd want to see the husband's character shine through in his words and actions, and the heroine's growth and depth as she navigates their relationship.  A proper introduction to the husband would make his death all the more impactful, allowing you to mourn his loss alongside the heroine and deepen your connection to her.  In short, you'd crave substance, not just the bare-bones storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As writers, our task is to deliver that substance.  It's tempting to rush past the details, especially when introducing new characters, but resist the urge.  Don't settle for a superficial "He used to be in the Air Force, now he's the night manager of a gas station, married twice, no kids, likes fishing on the weekends, dreams of owning the station, and loves Eggs Benedict."  Give your readers the richness they deserve - the meat on the bone of your story.

I caught a couple of local news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio – NBC 4's morning newscast on August 13, 2011, being the first. The breaking story was about a man named Shad Hostettler, who'd stabbed his wife in Ashley, Ohio. His mug shot was flashed on screen, and let's just say he didn't exactly exude innocence. The news team barely scratched the surface of the incident, devoting only two minutes to the developing story. I thought that was a fair amount of airtime, considering the gravity of the situation.

The next story was about an 18-year-old named Travis Buyers, who was shot in the Sharon Woods area. He was critically injured and the police were still looking for leads. I noticed that this story seemed to receive relatively short shrift, which made me wonder if the neighborhood or the victim's ethnicity might have played a role in it getting less attention. I've long been struck by the way the media often glosses over stories involving minorities. When a white person is a victim, the media goes into overdrive, but when it's a minority, they get shortchanged.

The newscast then moved on to a story about a gunshot hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. The authorities were tight-lipped about the investigation, but did reveal that a .22 caliber bullet had been fired from a rifle. A $5,000 reward was being offered for information that could lead to the shooter's capture.

Next up was a story about the impending rain and thunderstorms forecast for Saturday afternoon. The weather report was brief, and I think that was intentional – the anchor was using it as a teaser to keep viewers tuned in.

The broadcast also covered a robbery at a UDF store on Clime Road. The perp was described as a dark-skinned black man wearing a hoodie and a six-foot tall, 150-pound build. I found it interesting that the anchor emphasized the perpetrator's skin color and the color of his hoodie. It seemed like an unusual amount of time was spent on those details.

Another story was about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin who'd been convicted of conspiring to distribute large quantities of marijuana from Texas to Ohio. I was puzzled by the way the anchor phrased his sentence – instead of saying 25 years in prison, they said 300 months. It wasn't clear what the point of that was. The anchor also mentioned Rodriguez's Hispanic heritage, but I'm not sure why that was relevant to the story.

There's a bond between brothers that's impossible to break - a deep, unshakeable connection that weaves together a complex tapestry of emotions. Love, pride, jealousy, and the darker corners of cruelty all reside within this bond, creating a rich and multifaceted relationship that's both beautiful and brutal. Brothers have an uncanny understanding of one another, one that surpasses even the closest of friendships. When they look at each other, they see pieces of themselves, their own reflections staring back. It's in the darkest of times, when emotions run high, that the true nature of this bond is revealed, for better or for worse. With this bond comes a heavy price - the consequences of the emotions that fuel it. When we gaze into the eyes of a brother and see our own reflection staring back, we catch a glimpse of our true character, stripped bare of the facades we wear for the world. The choices we make and the actions we take are a testament to who we truly are.

In William Faulkner's "The Sound and the Fury" is not the correct text to be rewritten for the prompt, but instead, William Faulkner's short story "The Old Man" is not the correct text either. The story which is being rewritten is actually "The Scarlet Ibis" by Grant Wiggins. Through its vivid descriptions of a lush landscape, this tale of two brothers explores the intense emotions that come with this fraternal bond. In a heart-wrenching climax, bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride, and only one brother emerges unscathed. The author masterfully conveys the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist, Doodle, and his brother, as well as the narrator's observations, which serve as a powerful commentary on the true nature of their relationship. The protagonist's every move is driven by a single emotion: pride. From their early days together to their fateful final excursion, he harbors resentment towards his little brother, Doodle, who was born with a weak heart, making it impossible for him to participate in the adventurous life that his brother had envisioned. This crushing blow left the young protagonist reeling, his dreams of a playmate shattered in an instant. His anger towards Doodle is evident, as he even contemplates taking his life by suffocating him with a pillow - a chilling revelation that speaks to the darker corners of his heart. However, a simple smile from Doodle brings his brother's anger to the surface, revealing a glimmer of love and hope that had been lurking beneath. This moment of tenderness humanizes the protagonist, showing that his conviction was never as strong as he thought, and that love had always been present, even if it was hidden beneath the surface.

It's no secret that the human brain is a complex, ever-evolving machine that processes information in ways both mysterious and miraculous. As technology has advanced from the Stone Age to the digital age, the metaphors used to describe our brains have evolved as well. Initially, our brain was likened to a piece of wax, then a scroll, then a book, and most recently, a supercomputer. While these analogies have served as a starting point for our understanding, it's essential to remember that they're limited and can lead us down the rabbit hole of misconceptions.

So, let's dive into the brain's inner workings. Information starts its journey as sensory input from our organs, which convert physical stimuli such as touch, heat, light, or sound waves into electrical signals. The brain then takes over, processing this info through a series of intricate algorithms that involve both bottom-up and top-down processing. Imagine looking at a picture of a black box on a white background. Bottom-up processing would break down the image into its basic components – color, orientation, and object borders – to conclude that you're seeing a box. Top-down processing, on the other hand, uses the decisions made earlier to speed up your recognition, perhaps identifying the object as a black box rather than a hole in the background.

Once the brain has processed the information to a certain degree, an attention filter kicks in, deciding which signals are most important and which cognitive processes to engage. Think of it like trying to find your name in a crowded room – your brain filters out the noise and zooms in on what matters. This attention filter is a crucial step in information processing, and it's a process that happens repeatedly throughout.

For the brain to process information effectively, it first needs to store it. We have different types of memory – sensory, working, and long-term – each with its own unique characteristics. The process begins with encoding, where information is transformed into a format that the brain can understand. For example, verbal input can be encoded based on its visual appearance, sound, or meaning. From there, the information needs to be maintained, and research suggests that working memory stores data for about 20 seconds by creating an electrical loop through a series of neurons. Long-term memory, on the other hand, is thought to be stored in the structure of certain proteins.

There are many theories about how knowledge is organized in the brain, each with its own strengths and weaknesses. Some are based on human behavior, others on computer science, and others on neurophysiology. One such model, the semantic network, proposes that our brain represents concepts as nodes linked by their relatedness. For instance, in this network, "chair" might be connected to "table," which in turn is connected to "wooden," and so on.

Aldous Huxley's dystopian novel, Brave New World, serves as a scathing critique of the emerging technological and capitalistic structures of his time. In this fictional world, people prioritize community over individuality, and are conditioned from a young age to pursue instant gratification above all else. The citizens are mere pawns in a grand game, confined to a single ideology dictated by the all-powerful World Controller. Analyzing the novel through a Marxist lens reveals Huxley's underlying concerns about the developing systems. His use of Marxist terminology, such as homogeny and reification, underscores his suspicions about the flaws in the economy of his era.

Capitalism is satirized through the concept of false consciousness, where the common citizen is kept in the dark about their true relationships with other classes in economic terms. Instead, they are preoccupied with their own selfish interests. This ideological control is evident in the conditioning of the population through hypnopædia, which strengthens their drive to consume, spend, and indulge above all else. The World Controller manipulates this conditioning, as we've seen, to maintain the status quo. Hegemony, the idea of groups being dominated by a separate, more powerful group, is a clear example of this in Brave New World. The working classes are blissfully unaware of their manipulation, essentially buying into an ideology that upholds the system (capitalism and consumerism). Meanwhile, the upper classes are aware of the manipulation but choose to do nothing, accepting their place in the hierarchy.

In Huxley's world, genuine relationships between individuals are few and far between. The characters, even major ones, lack depth and substance. One cannot help but wonder if Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together strips people of their free will and self-expression. Love and intense emotions are nonexistent; interactions are kept superficial, as seen in the males' shallow comments about women's physical appearance and the females' candid discussions of their encounters. Furthermore, the complacency of each social class in their position within the hierarchy reflects the socioeconomic effects of capitalism, where the proletariat is falsely convinced of their superiority as long as they continue to consume, obey, and conform to their peers.

I've been a student at University Park for roughly two and a half years now – four and a half semesters, give or take. For many of us, navigating the campus can be a real challenge.
