The brain then takes over, processing this info through a series of intricate algorithms that involve both bottom-up and top-down processing. Imagine looking at a picture of a black box on a white background. Bottom-up processing would break down the image into its basic components – color, orientation, and object borders – to conclude that you're seeing a box. Top-down processing, on the other hand, uses the decisions made earlier to speed up your recognition, perhaps identifying the object as a black box rather than a hole in the background.

Once the brain has processed the information to a certain degree, an attention filter kicks in, deciding which signals are most important and which cognitive processes to engage. Think of it like trying to find your name in a crowded room – your brain filters out the noise and zooms in on what matters. This attention filter is a crucial step in information processing, and it's a process that happens repeatedly throughout.

For the brain to process information effectively, it first needs to store it. We have different types of memory – sensory, working, and long-term – each with its own unique characteristics. The process begins with encoding, where information is transformed into a format that the brain can understand. For example, verbal input can be encoded based on its visual appearance, sound, or meaning. From there, the information needs to be maintained, and research suggests that working memory stores data for about 20 seconds by creating an electrical loop through a series of neurons. Long-term memory, on the other hand, is thought to be stored in the structure of certain proteins.

There are many theories about how knowledge is organized in the brain, each with its own strengths and weaknesses. Some are based on human behavior, others on computer science, and others on neurophysiology. One such model, the semantic network, proposes that our brain represents concepts as nodes linked by their relatedness. For instance, in this network, "chair" might be connected to "table," which in turn is connected to "wooden," and so on.

Aldous Huxley's dystopian novel, Brave New World, serves as a scathing critique of the emerging technological and capitalistic structures of his time. In this fictional world, people prioritize community over individuality, and are conditioned from a young age to pursue instant gratification above all else. The citizens are mere pawns in a grand game, confined to a single ideology dictated by the all-powerful World Controller. Analyzing the novel through a Marxist lens reveals Huxley's underlying concerns about the developing systems. His use of Marxist terminology, such as homogeny and reification, underscores his suspicions about the flaws in the economy of his era.

Capitalism is satirized through the concept of false consciousness, where the common citizen is kept in the dark about their true relationships with other classes in economic terms. Instead, they are preoccupied with their own selfish interests. This ideological control is evident in the conditioning of the population through hypnopædia, which strengthens their drive to consume, spend, and indulge above all else. The World Controller manipulates this conditioning, as we've seen, to maintain the status quo. Hegemony, the idea of groups being dominated by a separate, more powerful group, is a clear example of this in Brave New World. The working classes are blissfully unaware of their manipulation, essentially buying into an ideology that upholds the system (capitalism and consumerism). Meanwhile, the upper classes are aware of the manipulation but choose to do nothing, accepting their place in the hierarchy.

In Huxley's world, genuine relationships between individuals are few and far between. The characters, even major ones, lack depth and substance. One cannot help but wonder if Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together strips people of their free will and self-expression. Love and intense emotions are nonexistent; interactions are kept superficial, as seen in the males' shallow comments about women's physical appearance and the females' candid discussions of their encounters. Furthermore, the complacency of each social class in their position within the hierarchy reflects the socioeconomic effects of capitalism, where the proletariat is falsely convinced of their superiority as long as they continue to consume, obey, and conform to their peers.

I've been a student at University Park for roughly two and a half years now – four and a half semesters, give or take. For many of us, navigating the campus can be a real challenge. My first year in the East Halls dorm, nestled in the far reaches of campus, was a testament to this. The trek from my digs in Stuart Hall to places like the Willard building, near the heart of campus, often took up to 25 minutes on foot, especially when the unpredictable Penn State weather decided to make its presence known. I spoke with an alum not much older than myself, and it turned out that not too long ago, the East Halls dorms were effectively separated from the rest of the university by a vast expanse of unused land. Fast forward to today, and that empty space has been transformed into a thriving complex of sports fields, sleek new buildings, and trendy apartments, including the new Creamery and health services building. As our campus continues to expand, so do our transportation woes. What's the solution to this mobility conundrum? On a college campus, I firmly believe that the bicycle is the answer. However, a bike alone won't cut it; students need to hop on and the campus infrastructure needs to cater to cyclists' needs.

I recently chatted with a friend who'd recently dusted off his bike after a few years away from it. He mused, "Bikes are great – for a few years, it wasn't cool to ride a bike, but it's the only way to get around." Beyond being great exercise, bicycling is a highly efficient mode of transportation. A hearty bowl of oatmeal and a bit of physical exertion can take you 30 miles or more. As someone who now resides off campus, just as far from the heart of campus as some dorms, I made the smart move of investing in a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, a 25-minute walk from my place. My trusty bike, on the other hand, can get me there in under 5 minutes, provided I pedal hard enough. The only catch is that Pollock Road is the most direct route to Thomas building, but it's not always the most bike-friendly road. I've found that walking has its merits, but I'm a busy bee and can't afford the extra time. Without my bike, walking would be my only reliable option, and it would add an extra 30-40 minutes to my day, devouring over two and a half hours every week. Factor in the time spent walking to and from other classes, appointments, and the like, and I'd be losing precious time I can ill afford to spare.
